english:
  title: A Letter in Reply to Park In-seok
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: "I humbly present this letter. On the [designated] day of this month, the monk Jung-eun arrived in the capital, and through him I received the magnificent composition you had sent. Upon opening the seal and unfolding your letter, its radiance flooded my eyes, and I found the language and meaning equally sublime—truly a work that transcends the threshold of ancient masters, beyond what even the finest minds of the Jin and Song dynasties could dare approach. The way you have arranged your sentiments is genuine and meticulous, flowing as if from the depths of sincerity itself, though you demur with excessive humility. Your praise illuminates far beyond what this humble and unworthy one could merit.\n\nNow you, sir, stand as a chosen exemplar of virtue and letters among the worthies of our time. Though you have endured hardship and danger, withdrawing far from the world's gaze seeking no renown, still your noble reputation only flourishes, and all eyes turn toward you in anticipation. This too echoes what Liu Zihou spoke of—that those profound in the arts cannot be diminished, however circumstances may constrain them. \n\nMoreover, the ancients held that strangers who meet once become as old friends, and when hearts accord in spirit, why measure seniority or the length of acquaintance? How much more so with you and me, who have already shared a moment of understanding. Yet when I read your letter, I find no words of that warmth and candor I might have hoped for. This puzzles me greatly. Could it be that because I am reckless and flawed, mocked by many, you offer courtesy on the surface while harboring disdain beneath?\n\nI have long accepted the ridicule of my age and become as one cast aside. Yet to go unheeded in this world is a common fate—what is rare is to be known by a true gentleman. Thus I have gazed from afar at your bearing, harboring the distant wish to serve even as your lowliest servant, though I dare not hope for such an honor. Should you, when others turn away, deign to offer me some small measure of regard, I would face death without regret.\n\nI pray you will understand this. With spring's warmth upon us, I trust you will nurture yourself in the Way and thus fulfill the distant hopes of this humble correspondent. I dare not say more, but remain ever respectful."
  footnotes:
    - 'Jung-eun (中隱): A Buddhist monk who served as courier between the two correspondents.'
    - 'Liu Zihou (柳子厚): Tang dynasty poet and philosopher Liu Zongyuan, referenced for his observation that talented individuals maintain their worth regardless of circumstance.'
    - The letter appears to be Lim Chun's response to critical commentary from Park In-seok regarding Lim's character and social standing, mixing gratitude with subtle recrimination.
